			<div class="content" id="post-content-1140240">
									

<p>Well, I can think of two possible reasons that they might use software to analyze this thing:</p>
<p>1. Class-D personnel are significantly more useful than a computer, and probably quite a bit harder to find. They can be feed things, be fed to things, clean the containment areas of things, worship things, dance for things, you get the picture. As such, I imagine that the Foundation would like any chance to have a computer do a job instead of using up a Class-D on it.</p>
<p>2. A researcher who designed the software for something else (or just because) pestered the administration to let them use their pet project, if only to justify the funding they receive. I can imagine the conversation going something like this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Doctor: Hey, you know that text and image analysis software I made?</p>
<p>Admin: (sigh) Yes, Doctor. What about it?</p>
<p>Doctor: Well, I heard about that book that does things to you when you read it, and I was just wondering-</p>
<p>Admin: Fine, you can use it, if it'll get you to shut up about it.</p>
<p>Doctor: [Squeals in childlike excitement]</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Either way, I think the software bit is kinda cool, so even if using a Class-D <em>would</em> be better, I'd keep it.</p>

